\begin{mdframed}
\section{Unordered Pairs}
\end{mdframed}

\textbf{Exercise 3.1.0} Consider the sets $ \emptyset $, $ \lbrace \emptyset \rbrace $, $ \lbrace \lbrace \emptyset \rbrace \rbrace$, etc.; Consider all  the pairs such as $ \lbrace \emptyset, \lbrace \emptyset \rbrace \rbrace$, formed by two of them; consider the pairs formed by any such two pairs, or else mixed pairs formed by a singleton and any pair; and proceed \textit{ad infinitum}. Are all the sets obtained in this way distinct from one another? 
 
 \bigbreak
 Yes, all sets obtained in this way are distinct. 
\begin{proof} 

\end{proof}

